@flexiarg relationship-coherence/quote-as-oblique-address
@title A Found Text Can Carry What Direct Speech Can't Yet Hold
@sigils [❝/借]
@keywords quote-gift, oblique-address, found-text, gloss, intimacy-at-one-remove, citation-as-bid, song-rec
@audience correspondents, close readers of a two-person canon
@references [relationship-coherence/lexicon-minting relationship-coherence/resonance-weaving]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-05-10 — Joe sends AN 10.176 (> 'He does not get sexually involved with those who are protected...') and immediately glosses it in his own voice ('I believe: you are better off not being protected...'), turning a scripture citation into a tender, serious statement about Julia's autonomy and her family. Generalised across Julia's 2026-03-26 Benjamin/Barthes/Barthes fragments ('A few fragments of text our conversation reminded me of today') and the running song-rec exchange (e.g. 2026-04-08 'my Roman Empire')."]
@tone declarative
@style pattern

! conclusion: When something is truer than the moment can yet hold plainly, send a found text as its vehicle — then gloss it in your own voice, so the citation becomes address rather than ornament.

  + context: A quote lets two people test or deepen intimacy at one remove: the recipient can meet the text first and the claim second. This is the dominant register of the Joe/Julia correspondence — Benjamin, Barthes, Deleuze, Spinoza, the Dhamma, Amina Cain, and a steady traffic of song links are how difficult or tender material first gets said.

  + IF:
    you hold a sentiment the direct register can't yet carry, and some passage or song says it for you — about the relationship, the other person, or the shared world.

  + HOWEVER:
    an unglossed quote reads as decoration or as evasion; the recipient cannot tell whether it is *about* them, or merely something you liked. The gift stalls at the level of taste.

  + THEN:
    pair the found text with one line in your own voice that names why you are sending it now — the gloss that converts a shared reading into a bid.

  + BECAUSE:
    the gloss makes the citation legible as address without over-stating it: it keeps the exchange deniable enough to be safe and specific enough to land. The quote carries the WHAT; your line carries the FOR-YOU.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - When receiving an unglossed gift, the coherent reply is to gloss it back ('this is so me, on so many levels' — 2026-03-27) rather than only to rate it.
    - Watch the failure twin, quote-flood: a burst of links with no glosses reverts the channel to taste-signalling. See relationship-coherence/resonance-weaving for how gifts get woven rather than piled.
